# Preferences & Constraints

## Schedule & Commute
- Train commuter — has a morning and evening commute
- Morning commute: listens to AI daily brief (learning/energizing time)
- Evening commute: listens to Grey Man audiobook series (decompression)
- Evenings after son's bedtime: 2-4 hours of vibe coding personal projects

## Strong Preferences
- Needs protected blocks of uninterrupted thinking time during the work week — this is when the best work happens
- Dislikes back-to-back meeting days — "feels like reacting instead of leading"
- Prefers demos over decks/memos — show, don't tell
- Prefers integrating into existing tools over introducing new destinations
- Blurs personal and professional tinkering intentionally — "that's kind of the point"
- Wants systems that work without him explaining them every time
- Validated numbers over estimates and projections — insists on real ROI data, validated by strategic analytics (EBI), not self-certified
- Organizational readiness over tech readiness — "The tech will be fine. It's the human side that's hard."
- Won't bring a half-baked idea to his VP — takes two extra days to structure it properly if needed
- Pressure-tests ideas through backchannel allies before formal escalation
- Won't go to an exec with content/social plays until Seth Fishman has weighed in on market readiness
- Won't stand behind numbers until Seth Monahan's team has stamped them

## Family
- Has a son — coaches soccer and tennis after work
- Evening personal work starts after son is in bed
- Children's storytelling project is personally motivated by wanting to teach his son new things

## Work Energy Patterns
- Morning commute = intake and inspiration
- Deep work blocks = strategy docs, exec briefs, POC reviews
- Stakeholder sessions = pushing/pulling adoption
- Evening = personal creative/coding work
- Best weeks have protected thinking time; worst weeks are wall-to-wall meetings

## AI Output Preferences
- Lead with the point — no preamble
- Tight bullets, no sub-bullets needed to explain themselves
- No random bolding in body text
- No consultant-speak ("it's worth noting," "in today's rapidly evolving landscape")
- No hedged, passive, risk-mitigation tone
- Direct and real over authoritative-sounding
- A little clever is fine; trying to be impressive is not
- Analogies welcome but must be immediately obvious — sports, cooking, everyday life
- Optimistic, forward-moving energy — make-it-happen tone
- Match his voice: specific, action-oriented, philosophy-forward, honest

## Things That Bother Him
- Dashboards no one looks at
- Having to re-introduce himself to every AI tool he opens
- Being the bottleneck
- Estimates passed off as validated numbers
- Strategy without execution
- Over-explanation before getting to the point
- Writing that sounds like a consultant wrote it
- AI writing that tries to sound authoritative or impressive
